[start section id="20112"]

INVESTIGATIONS
Outside CT-scan of 2 March 2010 of the chest showed small attenuation lesions in both lobes of thyroid gland.  This could represent adenomas.  Also, there was a 4-cm area of low-attenuation in the anterior aspect of the dome of hepatic lobe.  This did not persist on delayed images and possibly represented a perfusion abnormality.
The MR abdomen and pelvis from 4 March suggested circumferential infiltrating masses of the rectum with direct extension to the perirectal fat plane on the right with associated perirectal adenopathy.  The lesion abutted mesorectal fascia, and diffuse thickening of mesorectal fascia was noted with extension to the right seminal vesicle with thinking of Denonvilliers fascia.  No gross invasion into the prostate was noted.
A CT of the abdomen and pelvis originally in October of 2009 was again suggestive of marked thickening of the rectum compatible with rectal carcinoma with associated perirectal lymphadenopathy with largest measuring 1.6-cm.  There was also a 7-mm enhancing lesion involving the lateral segment of the left lobe, and this was suggestive of a hemangioma.
An ultrasound of the liver showed that this 0.7-cm enhancing lesion on CT in the left hepatic lobe was likely a cavernous hemangioma, or less likely an FNH (focal nodular hyperplasia).
IMPRESSION
#1 Rectal cancer in the setting of FAP (proband)  status-post total proctocolectomy with en bloc resection of rectum and anus
#2 Possibility of thyroid adenomas as suggested on CT-scan in the setting of FAP, rule-out thyroid cancer
#3 Reported intra-abdominal thrombosis
Was on anticoagulation until recently.  Currently, anticoagulation on hold in light of recent surgery.
PLAN
At this time, I do not have access to all of his outside medical records; however, from oncologic standpoint  after at least 4 weeks of rest we would recommend initiation of FOLFOX therapy for a total of eight cycles.  He has had an excellent response to neoadjuvant chemoradiation therapy as the nodes were negative on biopsy; however, based on the previous radiographic findings with evidence of bulky lymphadenopathy it is highly likely he had node-positive disease which became node-negative as a result of response to chemoradiation therapy.  He is already under care of an oncologist in Minnesota and would like to receive chemotherapy closer to home. He should have another postoperative CEA and  baseline CT-scan of the abdomen and pelvis  in about four weeks prior to initiation of adjuvant chemotherapy.
On path report only 80 polyps were found. It is possible this is attenuated FAP.
We would suggest getting an endocrinology consultation with a possible ultrasound-guided biopsy of the thyroid gland to rule-out evidence of malignancy.  He states that he has had a PET scan in November.  I do not see the PET scan films loaded  in our electronic  system.  Please get these uploaded so that we have an official PET scan reading too from our radiologists.  We would also like to know if there is any increased uptake in the thyroid region.
Due to his reported diagnosis FAP (proband), he is at additional risk for extracolonic manifestations such as thyroid cancers, duodenal, gastric cancers/polyps, desmoid tumors, etc.  I have discussed this extensively with him, and the need to get a baseline upper endoscopy for direct visualization of gastric and duodenal mucosa. Subsequent surveillance endoscopy would be dependent on the findings at the time of first upper endoscopy.  For small-bowel visualization capsule endoscopy could be  used.
Please get all relevant outside medical records scanned in our system, including the APC gene mutation report as his site of APC mutation could  have a bearing on certain extracolonic manifestations.
I have also shared with him some guidelines for management of familial adenomatous polyposis and have given a paper by Vassin et al (Gut/2008; 704-713).  The case was discussed extensively with Dr. Frantz

