[start section id="20103"]

Mr. Childs Brown is a very pleasant 29-year-old gentleman who was unfortunately diagnosed recently with rectal cancer in the setting of familial adenomatous polyposis (FAP).  His symptoms began in October 2009 when he started to experience constipation and a feeling of incomplete evacuation.  At that time, he also experienced rectal pressure/fullness and occasionally had hematochezia.  His symptoms started two-to-three weeks prior to presentation to his local MD.  In addition, he has had a weight-loss of about 15 pounds, particularly when he transitioned to liquid diet, with the hope that his symptoms would get resolved with dietary modifications.  He denies any fever, chills, loss of appetite, chest pain, shortness-of-breath, bone pain, or headaches.  He denies any neurological symptoms.  He does not have any family history of colon cancer . He states that he was diagnosed with familial adenomatous polyposis/FAP with genetic testing; and one of his siblings (brother) was also tested.  However, his brother did not have any abnormality in APC gene mutation.  His CT-scan  on October 18, 2009, showed an extensive rectal  tumor with external iliac adenopathy along with bulky lymphadenopathy in the pelvis.  He had a colonoscopy (per Dr. Nicole Davis's note on October 26), and a rectal mass with 75% circumferential involvement extending at least 5-cm into the rectum was noted.  There were at least a 100 polyps.  His CEA in November was 2.3.
He underwent loop ileostomy on November 27, 2009.  Then, in early December he was started on radiation with concurrent chemotherapy (Xeloda) which he received through January 23, 2010.  He received a total of 5400 cGy to the rectal tumor.
He was initially evaluated by Dr. Nicole Davis on February 10, 2010.  A plan for surgery with intraoperative radiation therapy was made at that time.
On March 23, 2010, he underwent total proctocolectomy with combined en bloc resection of rectum, anus, portion of seminal vesicles on the right-side, plus Denonvilliers fascia with a complex excision of the left external iliac lymph gland, and takedown loop ileostomy with ileoileostomy (end-to-end along with bilateral ureteral stent placement and intraoperative radiation therapy),  and 1000 cGy of IORT
The biopsy showed microscopic focus of residual moderately differentiated adenocarcinoma within fibrous tissue, associated with extensive mucin pools.  The margins were free of tumor.  In addition, vas deferens, right seminal vesicle, prostate anterior margin was free of any tumor cells.  His left external iliac lymph node biopsy was suggestive of fibrosis and necrosis.  There were multiple tubular (80) adenomata with low-grade dysplasia identified with six regional lymph nodes that were negative for tumor.  In addition, two ileocolic lymph nodes were also negative for tumor.
Medical Oncology was consulted for further recommendations regarding chemotherapy.

[end section id="20103"]

